{"title_page": "Byt\u010da", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Byt\u010da\n| native_name             = \n| other_name              = \n| settlement_type         = Town\n<!-- images, nickname, motto -->\n| image_skyline           = Zamky.Sk Bytca.jpg\n| image_caption           = [[Byt\u010da Castle]]\n| image_flag              = \n| image_shield            = Coat of arms of Byt\u010da.png\n| motto                   = \n| nickname                = \n| etymology               = \n<!-- location -->\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{SVK}}\n| subdivision_type1       = \n| subdivision_name1       = \n| subdivision_type2       = [[Regions of Slovakia|Region]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[\u017dilina Region|\u017dilina]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Districts of Slovakia|District]]\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Byt\u010da District|Byt\u010da]]\n| subdivision_type4       = \n| subdivision_name4       = \n<!-- maps and coordinates -->\n| image_map               = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = Slovakia \u017dilina Region#Slovakia\n| pushpin_relief          = 1\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location of Byt\u010da in Slovakia \n| coordinates             = {{coord|49|13|27|N|18|33|51|E|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n<!-- government type, leaders -->\n| leader_title            = Mayor\n| leader_name             = Miroslav Min\u00e1r\u010dik\n<!-- established -->\n| established_title       = First mentioned\n| established_date        = 1234\n<!-- area -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 43.168\n| area_total_sq_mi        = \n| area_land_sq_mi         = \n| area_water_sq_mi        = \n<!-- elevation -->\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 308\n| elevation_ft            = \n<!-- population -->\n| population_as_of        = 2018-12-31<ref>{{cite web |title=Population and migration |url=https://slovak.statistics.sk/wps/portal/ext/themes/demography/population/indicators/|publisher=Statistical Office of the Slovak Republic |accessdate=2019-04-16}}</ref>\n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 11340\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_sq_mi=\n| population_demonym      = \n<!-- time zone(s) -->\n| timezone1               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +1\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +2\n<!-- postal codes, area code -->\n| postal_code_type        = Postal code\n| postal_code             = 014 01\n| area_code_type          =  \n| area_code               = +421-41\n| geocode                 = \n| iso_code                = \n| blank_name              = [[Slovak car registration plates|Car plate]]\n| blank_info              = BY\n<!-- website, footnotes -->\n| website                 = [http://www.bytca.sk/index_en.html www.bytca.sk]\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Byt\u010da''' ({{lang-hu|Nagybiccse}}) is a town in northwestern [[Slovakia]]. It is located on the [[V\u00e1h]] River near the cities of [[\u017dilina]] and [[Pova\u017esk\u00e1 Bystrica]]. It belongs to [[Upper V\u00e1h region]] of tourism.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name comes from a Slavic personal name ''Bytek'', ''Bytko'' \u2192 ''Byt\u010da''.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Imrich |last=Hor\u0148ansk\u00fd |title=O geografick\u00fdch n\u00e1zvoch z osobn\u00fdch mien zo slovn\u00fdm z\u00e1kladom chot- |trans-title=Geographical Names from Personal Names with Word Basis of chot- |journal=Slovensk\u00e1 re\u010d |p=37 |year=2018 |issue=1 |issn= 1338-4279 |url=http://www.juls.savba.sk/ediela/sr/2018/1/sr18-1.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe town arose in 1946 by a merger of the settlements Mal\u00e1 Byt\u010da (including Be\u0148ov and Mik\u0161ov\u00e1), Ve\u013ek\u00e1 Byt\u010da and [[Hlin\u00edk nad V\u00e1hom]]. The first written reference to the town's main part Ve\u013ek\u00e1 Byt\u010da dates from 1234 as ''terra Bycha''.<ref>[http://www.bytca.sk/files/texts/historia_mesta/chronologia_bytce.htm Chronol\u00f3gia mesta Byt\u010da<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The settlement got its town charter in 1378. It was the seat of a feudal dominion and later a town with many craftsmen. In Hungarian, it was known as Biccse.\n\n==Landmarks==\nThe town features a famous castle the Thurz\u00f3 Castle built as a [[water castle]] by Pongr\u00e1c Szentmikl\u00f3si in the 13th century and rebuilt in the 16th century in [[Renaissance]] style by Ferenc Thurz\u00f3. The town also houses the Wedding Palace (built by [[Gy\u00f6rgy Thurz\u00f3]] for his daughters' wedding) from 1601, which is the only building of this kind in Slovakia, Renaissance, [[Baroque]] and [[classicism|Classical]] [[bourgeoisie]] houses, an archive, and a museum (in the Wedding Palace).\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the 2001 [[census]], the town had 11,150 inhabitants. 98.27% of inhabitants were [[Slovaks]] and 0.58% [[Czech people|Czechs]].<ref name=\"statistics\">{{cite web|title=Municipal Statistics |publisher=Statistical Office of the Slovak republic |url=http://www.statistics.sk/mosmis/eng/run.html |accessdate=2007-12-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071116010355/http://www.statistics.sk/mosmis/eng/run.html |archivedate=2007-11-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The religious make-up was 90.87% [[Roman Catholics]], 4.35% people with no religious affiliation and 1.51% [[Lutherans]].<ref name=\"statistics\"/>\n\n==Economy==\nToday, the town is home to machine (Kinex), textile, wood processing (sports equipment), and food (brewery) industries. The brewery closed in the 2010s.\n\n==Boroughs==\nByt\u010da includes the following former villages: Psurnovice, Hrabove, Horne Hlboke, Dolne Hlboke, Hlboke nad Vahom, Benov, Miksova, Hlinik nad Vahom, Velka Bytca, Mala Bytca.<ref>[http://www.cisarik.com/0_Bytca_Bytca_ZI_Trencsen_Trencin.html]</ref>\n\nCurrent boroughs (year of merger in brackets):\n*Be\u0148ov (c. 1899 with Mal\u00e1 Byt\u010da, probably Hungarian name was Banya)\n*Hlin\u00edk nad V\u00e1hom (1946, {{lang-hu|Hlinik}}; also called V\u00e1gagyagos between 1899 and 1919)\n*[[Hrabov\u00e9 (Slovakia)|Hrabov\u00e9]] (1971; {{lang-hu|Hrabova}}; also called Rab\u00f3 between 1899 and 1919)\n*Mal\u00e1 Byt\u010da (1946; {{lang-hu|Kisbiccse}}, {{lang-de|Klein-Bitsch}}; also called Miksofalva from 1907 to 1919) \n*Mik\u0161ov\u00e1 (1907 with Mal\u00e1 Byt\u010da, {{lang-hu|Miks\u00f3falv\u00e1}})\n*P\u0161urnovice (1971; {{lang-hu|Psurnovicz}}; also called Legel\u0151v\u00f6lgy between 1899 and 1919)\n*Ve\u013ek\u00e1 Byt\u010da (1946; {{lang-hu|Nagybiccse}}, {{lang-de|Gro\u00df-Bitsch}})\n\n==Twin towns \u2014 sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Slovakia}}\n\nByt\u010da is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=Partnersk\u00e9 mest\u00e1|url=http://www.bytca.sk/partnerske-mesta/|website=bytca.sk|publisher=Byt\u010da|language=sk|accessdate=2019-09-08}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|CZE}} [[Karolinka]], Czech Republic\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Opoczno]], Poland\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Adolf Neubauer]], Jewish scholar\n*[[Jozef Tiso]] (1887\u20131947) , Slovak priest, politician and leader of the First Slovak Republic (1939\u20131945) executed for war crimes\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of municipalities and towns in Slovakia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Genealogical resources==\n\nThe records for genealogical research are available at the state archive \"Statny Archiv in Bytca, Slovakia\"\n\n* Roman Catholic church records (births/marriages/deaths): 1630-1900 (parish A)\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bytca.sk/index_en.html Official municipal website]\n*[http://www.cisarik.com/0_Bytca_Bytca_ZI_Trencsen_Trencin.html'''Surnames''' of living people in Bytca]\n\n{{Byt\u010da District}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bytca}}\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Castles in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Villages and municipalities in Byt\u010da District]]\n[[Category:Geography of \u017dilina Region]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1946]]\n[[Category:1946 establishments in Czechoslovakia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Byt\u010da\n| native_name             = \n| other_name              = \n| settlement_type         = Town\n<!-- images, nickname, motto -->\n| image_skyline           = Zamky.Sk Bytca.jpg\n| image_caption           = [[Byt\u010da Castle]]\n| image_flag              = \n| image_shield            = Coat of arms of Byt\u010da.png\n| motto                   = \n| nickname                = \n| etymology               = \n<!-- location -->\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{SVK}}\n| subdivision_type1       = \n| subdivision_name1       = \n| subdivision_type2       = [[Regions of Slovakia|Region]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[\u017dilina Region|\u017dilina]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Districts of Slovakia|District]]\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Byt\u010da District|Byt\u010da]]\n| subdivision_type4       = \n| subdivision_name4       = \n<!-- maps and coordinates -->\n| image_map               = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = Slovakia \u017dilina Region#Slovakia\n| pushpin_relief          = 1\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location of Byt\u010da in Slovakia \n| coordinates             = {{coord|49|13|27|N|18|33|51|E|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n<!-- government type, leaders -->\n| leader_title            = Mayor\n| leader_name             = Miroslav Min\u00e1r\u010dik\n<!-- established -->\n| established_title       = First mentioned\n| established_date        = 1234\n<!-- area -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 43.168\n| area_total_sq_mi        = \n| area_land_sq_mi         = \n| area_water_sq_mi        = \n<!-- elevation -->\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 308\n| elevation_ft            = \n<!-- population -->\n| population_as_of        = 2018-12-31<ref>{{cite web |title=Population and migration |url=https://slovak.statistics.sk/wps/portal/ext/themes/demography/population/indicators/|publisher=Statistical Office of the Slovak Republic |accessdate=2019-04-16}}</ref>\n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 11340\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_sq_mi=\n| population_demonym      = \n<!-- time zone(s) -->\n| timezone1               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +1\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +2\n<!-- postal codes, area code -->\n| postal_code_type        = Postal code\n| postal_code             = 014 01\n| area_code_type          =  \n| area_code               = +421-41\n| geocode                 = \n| iso_code                = \n| blank_name              = [[Slovak car registration plates|Car plate]]\n| blank_info              = BY\n<!-- website, footnotes -->\n| website                 = [http://www.bytca.sk/index_en.html www.bytca.sk]\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Byt\u010da''' ({{lang-hu|Nagybiccse}}) is a town in northwestern [[Slovakia]]. It is located on the [[V\u00e1h]] River near the cities of [[\u017dilina]] and [[Pova\u017esk\u00e1 Bystrica]]. It belongs to [[Upper V\u00e1h region]] of tourism.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name comes from a Slavic personal name ''Bytek'', ''Bytko'' \u2192 ''Byt\u010da''.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Imrich |last=Hor\u0148ansk\u00fd |title=O geografick\u00fdch n\u00e1zvoch z osobn\u00fdch mien zo slovn\u00fdm z\u00e1kladom chot- |trans-title=Geographical Names from Personal Names with Word Basis of chot- |journal=Slovensk\u00e1 re\u010d |p=37 |year=2018 |issue=1 |issn= 1338-4279 |url=http://www.juls.savba.sk/ediela/sr/2018/1/sr18-1.pdf}}</ref>  \n==History==\nThe town arose in 1946 by a merger of the settlements Mal\u00e1 Byt\u010da (including Be\u0148ov and Mik\u0161ov\u00e1), Ve\u013ek\u00e1 Byt\u010da and [[Hlin\u00edk nad V\u00e1hom]]. The first written reference to the town's main part Ve\u013ek\u00e1 Byt\u010da dates from 1234 as ''terra Bycha''.<ref>[http://www.bytca.sk/files/texts/historia_mesta/chronologia_bytce.htm Chronol\u00f3gia mesta Byt\u010da<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The settlement got its town charter in 1378. It was the seat of a feudal dominion and later a town with many craftsmen. In Hungarian, it was known as Biccse.\n\n==Landmarks==\nThe town features a famous castle the Thurz\u00f3 Castle built as a [[water castle]] by Pongr\u00e1c Szentmikl\u00f3si in the 13th century and rebuilt in the 16th century in [[Renaissance]] style by Ferenc Thurz\u00f3. The town also houses the Wedding Palace (built by [[Gy\u00f6rgy Thurz\u00f3]] for his daughters' wedding) from 1601, which is the only building of this kind in Slovakia, Renaissance, [[Baroque]] and [[classicism|Classical]] [[bourgeoisie]] houses, an archive, and a museum (in the Wedding Palace).\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the 2001 [[census]], the town had 11,150 inhabitants. 98.27% of inhabitants were [[Slovaks]] and 0.58% [[Czech people|Czechs]].<ref name=\"statistics\">{{cite web|title=Municipal Statistics |publisher=Statistical Office of the Slovak republic |url=http://www.statistics.sk/mosmis/eng/run.html |accessdate=2007-12-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071116010355/http://www.statistics.sk/mosmis/eng/run.html |archivedate=2007-11-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The religious make-up was 90.87% [[Roman Catholics]], 4.35% people with no religious affiliation and 1.51% [[Lutherans]].<ref name=\"statistics\"/>\n\n==Economy==\nToday, the town is home to machine (Kinex), textile, wood processing (sports equipment), and food (brewery) industries. The brewery closed in the 2010s.\n\n==Boroughs==\nByt\u010da includes the following former villages: Psurnovice, Hrabove, Horne Hlboke, Dolne Hlboke, Hlboke nad Vahom, Benov, Miksova, Hlinik nad Vahom, Velka Bytca, Mala Bytca.<ref>[http://www.cisarik.com/0_Bytca_Bytca_ZI_Trencsen_Trencin.html]</ref>\n\nCurrent boroughs (year of merger in brackets):\n*Be\u0148ov (c. 1899 with Mal\u00e1 Byt\u010da, probably Hungarian name was Banya)\n*Hlin\u00edk nad V\u00e1hom (1946, {{lang-hu|Hlinik}}; also called V\u00e1gagyagos between 1899 and 1919)\n*[[Hrabov\u00e9 (Slovakia)|Hrabov\u00e9]] (1971; {{lang-hu|Hrabova}}; also called Rab\u00f3 between 1899 and 1919)\n*Mal\u00e1 Byt\u010da (1946; {{lang-hu|Kisbiccse}}, {{lang-de|Klein-Bitsch}}; also called Miksofalva from 1907 to 1919) \n*Mik\u0161ov\u00e1 (1907 with Mal\u00e1 Byt\u010da, {{lang-hu|Miks\u00f3falv\u00e1}})\n*P\u0161urnovice (1971; {{lang-hu|Psurnovicz}}; also called Legel\u0151v\u00f6lgy between 1899 and 1919)\n*Ve\u013ek\u00e1 Byt\u010da (1946; {{lang-hu|Nagybiccse}}, {{lang-de|Gro\u00df-Bitsch}})\n\n==Twin towns \u2014 sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Slovakia}}\n\nByt\u010da is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=Partnersk\u00e9 mest\u00e1|url=http://www.bytca.sk/partnerske-mesta/|website=bytca.sk|publisher=Byt\u010da|language=sk|accessdate=2019-09-08}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|CZE}} [[Karolinka]], Czech Republic\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Opoczno]], Poland\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Adolf Neubauer]], Jewish scholar\n*[[Jozef Tiso]] (1887\u20131947) , Slovak priest, politician and leader of the First Slovak Republic (1939\u20131945) executed for war crimes\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of municipalities and towns in Slovakia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Genealogical resources==\n\nThe records for genealogical research are available at the state archive \"Statny Archiv in Bytca, Slovakia\"\n\n* Roman Catholic church records (births/marriages/deaths): 1630-1900 (parish A)\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bytca.sk/index_en.html Official municipal website]\n*[http://www.cisarik.com/0_Bytca_Bytca_ZI_Trencsen_Trencin.html'''Surnames''' of living people in Bytca]\n\n{{Byt\u010da District}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bytca}}\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Castles in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Villages and municipalities in Byt\u010da District]]\n[[Category:Geography of \u017dilina Region]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1946]]\n[[Category:1946 establishments in Czechoslovakia]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Byt%C4%8Da"}
